entries.title: US biotech Nabla Bio, Japan's Takeda expand AI drug design partnership
entries.snippet:
U.S. biotechnology company Nabla Bio has announced an expanded research partnership with Japan’s Takeda Pharmaceutical to enhance drug discovery using artificial intelligence. Building on a 2022 collaboration, the new multi-year agreement will provide Nabla with upfront and research payments in the "double-digit millions," along with the potential for over $1 billion in success-based milestone payments. Central to the partnership is Nabla's proprietary AI platform, the Joint Atomic Model (JAM), which rapidly designs protein-based therapeutics tailored to Takeda’s early-stage pipeline, focusing on challenging diseases with complex biologics.

Nabla CEO Surge Biswas compared JAM's functionality to how ChatGPT answers questions, except JAM designs antibodies tailored to specific targets. The AI platform enables a rapid three to four-week turnaround from design to laboratory testing, which Nabla claims is the industry's fastest. This agreement highlights the pharmaceutical industry's growing reliance on AI to reduce drug development timelines and costs. Takeda recently pivoted away from cell therapy research to concentrate on more scalable drug types and has also joined a consortium, including Bristol Myers Squibb, to train AI models with shared data. Nabla anticipates human trial results from AI-designed molecules within one to two years.

entries.title: OpenAI-backed Chai raises $70mn for AI-driven drug discovery
entries.snippet:
Chai Discovery, a two-year-old AI-driven drug discovery startup backed by OpenAI, has raised $70 million in funding, bringing its valuation to approximately $550 million. The round included investment from Menlo Ventures, DST Global Partners, and Yosemite, along with existing backers like Thrive Capital and OpenAI. Chai aims to revolutionize drug development by using artificial intelligence to design molecules and antibodies that can bind to proteins and potentially treat diseases, including those previously seen as "undruggable."

Co-founded by Joshua Meier and Jack Dent, the company’s latest model, Chai-2, has shown significantly higher hit rates in early tests—one in six proteins successfully targeted, compared to the traditional one in a thousand. Chai plans to commercialize its AI model through partnerships with pharmaceutical companies and has appointed former Pfizer CSO Mikael Dolsten to its board. Despite the inflow of capital into AI-driven biotech, industry results remain early-stage, with no AI-discovered drugs yet approved. Nonetheless, investors express optimism, seeing Chai’s combination of deep AI capabilities and biological expertise as poised to disrupt the biopharma sector.

entries.title: Alphabet's Isomorphic Labs raises $600M in first funding round for AI drug business
entries.snippet: Isomorphic Labs, Alphabet's AI-driven drug discovery initiative, raised $600M in its initial external funding round, led by Thrive Capital with participation from Google Ventures and further backing from Alphabet. Launched in 2021 and based in London, the company's mission is to "solve all disease" by leveraging artificial intelligence to accelerate breakthroughs in drug design. Known for developing AlphaFold, a Nobel Prize-winning AI platform that predicts protein structures quickly, Isomorphic Labs intends to use the new funds to enhance its next-generation AI drug design engine, progress clinical development programs, and expand its team. CEO Demis Hassabis, who also leads DeepMind Technologies, highlighted the funding's role in advancing their ambitious goals. Pharmaceutical giants such as Eli Lilly and Novartis are among their partners. Other Alphabet health-related subsidiaries include Verily and Calico.

parts:
Here’s a crisp state-of-the-art snapshot (late-2025) across folding, modeling, and drug discovery—with the most consequential shifts and why they matter.

# Folding & complex prediction
- **AlphaFold 3 (DeepMind/Isomorphic, 2024)** moved from single proteins to **joint complex prediction** (proteins, nucleic acids, ligands, ions, PTMs) using a diffusion-style architecture. This lifted docking-like use cases from “nice demo” to genuinely useful *in silico* hypotheses for binders and multimers. citeturn0search1turn0search16  
- **OpenFold3 (2025)**: the open-source community’s push toward AF3-class capability—important for reproducibility, transparency, and custom training. It’s early, but signals a credible open alternative for complex modeling. citeturn0search0

# Sequence↔structure↔function generative models
- **ESM3 (EvolutionaryScale, 2024–2025)**: a “frontier” multimodal protein LM that **reasons over sequence, structure, and function** and can *generate* functional proteins (e.g., new fluorescent proteins). This blurs the line between folding and **programmable biology**, enabling design conditioned on function. citeturn0search2turn0search9turn0search17
- **RareFold (2025 preprint)** expands prediction/design to **non-canonical amino acids**, widening chemical search space beyond the standard 20 AAs, which is critical for stability, specificity, and IP-novelty. citeturn0search10

# Structure-guided design & docking
- **RFdiffusion → antibody/binder design (2025)**: fine-tuned diffusion networks now produce **atomically precise de novo antibodies** against user-specified epitopes—with experimental validation. That’s a major step for targeted biologics. citeturn0search3
- **DiffDock-L (2024)** significantly improved ligand docking performance and generalization, becoming a practical baseline for **pose prediction** and screening with AF3-like inputs. citeturn0search7turn0search14

# Industry platforms & pipelines
- **Isomorphic Labs (Alphabet)**: raised substantial external capital and **preparing first AI-designed molecules for human trials**—an important reality check on end-to-end pipelines from *in silico* to clinic. citeturn0news86turn0search4turn0search19
- **Generate:Biomedicines**: continued platform updates and a broad clinical-stage pipeline for “programmable” protein medicines (enzymes, antibodies, more). citeturn0search5turn0search12turn0search20
- **NVIDIA BioNeMo (2025)**: maturing compute/software stack for biopharma (foundation models, microservices, e.g., **MolMIM** for small-molecule generation)—reducing infra friction for teams to train/deploy bespoke models. citeturn0search21turn0search6turn0search13
- **Partnership momentum**: e.g., **Nabla Bio × Takeda** scaling AI antibody design with a fast “design→test” loop; **Chai Discovery** funding for high-hit-rate design (antibodies/small molecules). These signal pharma’s shift from pilots to **platform-integrated programs**. citeturn0news80turn0news81

# What’s actually new (substance vs. hype)
1) **From folding to interacting systems.** AF3-class models treat **complexes** (protein–protein/DNA/RNA/ligands/ions) as first-class citizens—key for binding mode hypotheses and rational design. citeturn0search1  
2) **Generative + physics-aware training.** Diffusion/LangModels are no longer “pretty structures”; they’re **function-conditioned** and increasingly **atomistically checked** (e.g., RFdiffusion antibodies). Expect tighter integration with ML-based scoring and QM/MD refinements. citeturn0search3  
3) **Wet-lab feedback loops.** Partnerships now emphasize **closed-loop design-build-test-learn** with cycle times measured in **weeks**, not months—critical to move past retrospective “benchmarks.” citeturn0news80  
4) **Platformization.** Tooling (BioNeMo etc.) is standardizing data, training, and inference, letting small teams run AF3-era workflows without bespoke infra. citeturn0search21  
5) **Beyond canonical biology.** Models like RareFold aim at **expanded alphabets** and post-translational chemistries—unlocking stability and specificity inaccessible to natural proteins. citeturn0search10

# Near-term implications for drug discovery
- **Target triage & hit finding:** AF3 + DiffDock-L + generative chem (e.g., MolMIM) enable richer **in silico triage** before synthesis—fewer dead-ends, better priors. citeturn0search1turn0search7turn0search13  
- **Biologics on demand:** RFdiffusion-style pipelines for **de novo antibodies/VHHs** against predefined epitopes compress months of discovery into iterative weeks. citeturn0search3  
- **Data flywheels:** ESM3-type models benefit massively from **assay feedback**; groups with automated labs will compound advantages fastest. citeturn0search2  
- **Regulatory reality:** Despite capital and excitement, **no AI-discovered drug is approved yet**; 2025–2027 trials will be the gut-check for clinical translation and ROI. (Industry funding/trial prep news reflects this pivot to evidence.) citeturn0news81turn0search4

If you want, I can map these to an end-to-end “stack” for your use (folding/complexing → docking/scoring → generative design → validation → MD/QM → active-learning loop), with open models/tools and compute notes.
